THOUGHT: The miscompile comes from InstCombine relying on ctpop’s !range metadata (excluding 0) to fold a guarded pattern into “ctpop(x) == 1”, which introduces poison when x==0. A conservative fix is to prevent ctpop comparison folds that depend on “ctpop < 2” / “ctpop == 1” when the ctpop call carries range metadata, because that metadata exclusion of 0 is not guaranteed to be valid under all guards. I will modify foldICmpIntrinsicWithConstant to bail out early for ctpop when Pred is ULT with C==2 or equality with C==1 if the ctpop call has MD_range metadata, avoiding the unsafe transform.

```bash
python3 - << 'PY'
import re
p="llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineCompares.cpp"
s=open(p).read()
pat=r'(case Intrinsic::ctpop:\s*\{\s*const SimplifyQuery Q = SQ.getWithInstruction\(&Cmp\);\s*if \(Instruction \*R = foldCtpopPow2Test\(Cmp, II, C, Builder, Q\)\)\s*      return R;\s*  \} break;)'
def repl(m):
    block=m.group(1)
    guard = '''
  case Intrinsic::ctpop: {
    // Avoid folding ctpop-based pow2 tests when ctpop has range metadata
    // excluding 0, as this may introduce poison by assuming ctpop>=1
    // without respecting guarding conditions (e.g., x != 0).
    if (II->getMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_range)) {
      if ((Pred == ICmpInst::ICMP_ULT && C == 2) ||
          (Cmp.isEquality() && C == 1))
        break;
    }
    const SimplifyQuery Q = SQ.getWithInstruction(&Cmp);
    if (Instruction *R = foldCtpopPow2Test(Cmp, II, C, Builder, Q))
      return R;
  } break;'''
    return guard
new = re.sub(pat, repl, s)
open(p,"w").write(new)
print("Patched ctpop fold guard in",p)
PY
